definition.value: An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is ethane substituted by carboxyl groups at positions 1 and 2.
An azamacrocycle with formula C34H32N8O7S isolated from the cultured mycelium of Streptomyces nobilis. It exhibits potent cytotoxic activity against human cancer cell lines.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-threonyl-L-threonine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-threonyl-L-serine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-seryl-L-threonine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of glycyl-L-histidine; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-alanyl-L-cysteine; major species at pH 7.3.
The O-phospho derivative of L-histidinol.
A composition-only glycan consisting of four hexosyl groups, two acetaminohexosyl groups, and one 6-deoxyhexosyl group (identities and connectivity unknown). Composition: Hex4 HexNAc2 dHex1.

The simplest member of the class of propane-1,2-diols, consisting of propane in which a hydrogen at position 1 and a hydrogen at position 2 are substituted by hydroxy groups. A colourless, viscous, hygroscopic, low-melting (-59degreeC) and high-boiling (188degreeC) liquid with low toxicity, it is used as a solvent, emulsifying agent, and antifreeze.
A nucleoside triphosphate(4-) obtained by global deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of 2-hydroxy-ATP; major species present at pH 7.3.
A nucleoside 5'-monophosphate(2-) that results from the removal of two protons from the phosphate group of 2-hydroxy-AMP. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
Major microspecies at pH 7.3

A lysoglycerophospholipid that has an acyl group at position sn-1.
A disaccharide phosphate that is N-acetyl-6-O-phospho-beta-D-glucosamine having a beta-D-galactosyl residue attached at O-4.
The D-enantiomer of phenylalanine.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of cis,cis-2,4-dihydroxy-5-methyl-6-oxo-2,4-hexadienoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2,4-dihydroxy-5-methyl-6-oxo-2,4-hexadienoic acid in which both double bonds adopt a trans-configuration.

A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of trans,trans-2,4-dihydroxy-5-methyl-6-oxo-2,4-hexadienoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

A branched amino pentasaccharide consisting of a linear tetrasaccharide comprising N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine, beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine and N-acetyl-D-galactosamine residues linked sequentially (1->3), (1->4) and (1->6), to the beta-D-galactosamine of which is also linked (1->2) an alpha-L-fucosyl residue.
A sesterterpenoid with formula C25H38O2 which is isolated from the fungus Emericella variecolor.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that results from the deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group of tropic acid.
A tertiary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of dilazep resulting from the protonation of the two amino groups of the diazepane moiety.
An amino tetrasaccharide comprising alpha-D-galactose, beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine and alpha-D-mannose residues linked sequentially (1->3), (1->4) and (1->2).

A branched amino pentasaccharide comprising alpha-D-galactose, beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine and alpha-D-mannose residues linked sequentially (1->3), (1->4) and (1->2), to the beta-D-galactose residue of which is also linked (1->2) an alpha-L-fucosyl residue.

A branched amino pentasaccharide comprising N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine, beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine and alpha-D-mannose residues linked sequentially (1->3), (1->4) and (1->2), to the beta-D-galactose residue of which is also linked (1->2) an alpha-L-fucosyl residue.
